GOD HAS ANSWERED MY PRAYERS! I can not express my excitement enough how truly happy I am that an actual authentic cantonese/hongkong-style restaurant has finalllyyy came to Bay Ridge... literally right there from my house too! Now this girl here no longer has to lay in her bed, suffering for hours until she somehow finds the power to get up and out the house or somehow receives her congee/soup to cure her hangovers on the weekends. So apparently this place is originally quite a popular eatery in Flushing that's now made it's way to Brooklyn. Honestly, I lived here for 13 years... and there's probably been 10 new restaurants here already... it's like this spot is cursed but I really want this one to stay forever because WE NEED THIS TYPE OF FOOD IN BAYRIDGE! I'm a huge advocate for E Noodle Cafe because its actually good!  FRIED FISH SKIN - CRACK. I was surprised to see this on the menu because I love ordering this at hotpot places.. and this place does it so well! Very crispy and super seasoned to the max. And its accompanied with soup on the side to dip.  TRADITIONAL HK POT RICE - aka "bo jai fon" in chinese. Honestly there's no place that does bo jai fon good in Brooklyn at all besides possibly just the eel one from Lian Won Cafe in Bensonhurst. My girls loved it and truly feel like its more tastier than the ones at King's too. Plus they're super generous with the meat toppings in this. Those who don't know what this dish is, GET IT... MIX IT! &Of course, how can you get bo jai fon without an egg?  CRABMEAT SOUP DUMPLINGS - aka xlb(xiao long baos) I love soup dumplings so much that I can have it all day, everyday, any weather and especially after a hangover. So you can imagine the tears that came to my eyes when theres one right by my house now... and that actually tops all of the other few restaurants that has soup dumplings in Brooklyn now. The skin is a little different than traditional ones used for these, they're still thin but in a sense, a tad chewier and sort of impossible to "pop"/"leak"... and these soup dumplings from here are VERY soupy compared to all the ones in Brooklyn, with actual generous taste of crab in there. Tears of joy in my eyes still.  HK STYLE LO MEIN - we got the beef brisket&beef tendon one because it was recommended by everyone from the restaurant plus its a big staple all over Asia. It's not the best I've had, but its still good. I must point out that I noticed the noodles itself tasted very fresh and homemade, with a good bounce to them. If you're gonna get this, you might wanna ask for extra sauce from the beef brisket to pour additionally into this dish. **Note to picky eaters: there's an option with just the beef brisket itself, without the tendons... but hey picky eaters probably wouldn't even enjoy that.  I'm highly impressed at their extensive congee list, I can't wait to walk over here to try it next!

There's something about their chicken noodle soup that I just love. I eat that meal 2 to 3 times a week and never get tired of it. They give a little saucer or red spicy sauce and I dump it in there, swirl it around.. heaven in a bowl! The only complaint I have is when I order from them online, I always try to ask them to add some vegetables to the soup, like mushrooms and/or chinese broccoli... but they NEVER ONCE abided my request. I admit that is a bit annoying but I can't argue with the quality of what I get. The noodles in the soup always taste fresh and have a great texture. They're silky-smooth-slippery and just the right amount of chewy. My stomach feels good after eating it.. not like other junk food Chinese places. The other thing I usually get is the vegetarian spring rolls. Surprising, they're consistently crunchy and fresh tasting. Anyway, this is one of my regular places and look forward to it every time!

Went here with my husband on a recommendation, and I was not disappointed. The food here is amazing! We got the Oxtail Curry and the Monster Ramen, and both were delicious. They didn't skimp with the ingredients - mine came with shrimp, squid, fish, fish cakes, mussels, and more (I hate getting cheated with proteins). The best was definitely the Crab Soup Dumplings. I expected crab dumplings that were cooked in soup. No. These dumplings actually had soup IN them, with some kind of meaty crab filling. There's no dessert section, but we finished off with Fried Dumplings (which were basically little yeast cakes) with Sweetened Condensed Milk ; they tasted like fresh cinnamon buns minus the cinnamon.  I am very, very full, and very, very happy. Also, the bill for the both of us came out to less than I usually pay for one of us, so there’s that affordable bonus too.
